The '''Niiname-sai''' (新嘗祭, also read '''Jinshō-sai''' and '''Niiname-no-Matsuri''') is a Japanese harvest ritual.

== Ceremony ==
During the Niiname-sai, an ancient Shinto ritual that says thanks for the crops of the previous year{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} and prays for fruitfulness in the following year,{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} the [[Emperor of Japan]] says thanks to the {{illm|gods of heaven and earth|ja|天津神・国津神}}.{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} It is held in the [[Imperial Palace]],{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} as well as [[Ise Shrine]]{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} and [[Izumo Shrine]].{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}}

== Date ==
Traditionally, it was held on the last [[rabbit (zodiac)|Day of the Rabbit]] in the eleventh month of the [[Japanese calendar|old lunar calendar]].{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}}

Since the [[Meiji era]] the date has been fixed on [[November 23]],{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} which corresponds to the modern public holiday [[Labor Thanksgiving Day]].{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}}

As a ''[[kigo]]'', the name of the ritual is associated with [[winter]].{{sfnm|1a1=Digital Daijisen|1y=1998a}}

== Name ==
''Niiname-sai'' is the common name of the festival, but the same kanji can also be read ''Jinshō-sai''{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} or ''Niiname-no-Matsuri''.{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}}

The first Niiname-sai following the accession of a new emperor is called the ''Daijō-sai'' (大嘗祭, also read ''Ōname-Matsuri'' and ''Ōnie-no-Matsuri'').{{sfnm|1a1=Digital Daijisen|1y=1998}}<!-- Britannica also verifies this, but not the readings, and Britannica's separate article 大嘗祭 actually doesn't give the reading おおなめまつり. -->

