{{Infobox holiday | holiday_name = Niiname-no-Matsuri | type = | image = | imagesize = | caption = | official_name = | nickname = | observedby = Japan | litcolor = | longtype = Religious | significance = [[harvest festival|harvest ritual]] | date = November 23 | scheduling = same day each year | celebrations = | observances = | relatedto = [[Labor Thanksgiving Day]], [[Daijosai]] }} The '''Niiname-sai''' (新嘗祭, also read '''Shinjō-sai''' and '''Niiname-no-Matsuri''') is a Japanese [[harvest festival|harvest ritual]].
The ritual is celebrated by the [[Emperor of Japan]], who thanks the [[Shinto]] deities for a prosperous year and prays for a fruitful new year. It takes place near the [[Three Palace Sanctuaries]] of in the imperial palace and several large [[Shinto shrine]]s. The first Niiname-sai for a new emperor is known as the Daijō-sai (大嘗祭), and is part of his [[Enthronement of the Japanese emperor|enthronement ceremonies]].
In pre-modern Japan, the date of the Niiname-sai was moveable, taking place on the last [[rabbit (zodiac)|Day of the Rabbit]] of the eleventh month of the old Japanese lunar calendar, but in the [[Meiji period]] the date was fixed at [[November 23]], and this date became a national holiday, [[Labor Thanksgiving Day]], in the [[Shōwa period]] after World War II.
== Ceremony == During the Niiname-sai, an ancient Shinto ritual that says thanks for the crops of the previous year{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} and prays for fruitfulness in the following year,{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} the [[Emperor of Japan]] says thanks to his [[kami|gods]]. It is held in the [[Tokyo Imperial Palace|Imperial Palace]],{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} as well as other shrines including [[Ise Grand Shrine]]{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} and [[Izumo Shrine]].{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}}
== Date == Traditionally, it was held on the last [[rabbit (zodiac)|Day of the Rabbit]] in the eleventh month of the [[Japanese calendar|old lunar calendar]].{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}}
Since the [[Meiji era]] the date has been fixed on [[November 23]],{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} which corresponds to the modern public holiday [[Labor Thanksgiving Day]],{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} which was introduced in 1948.
As a ''[[kigo]]'', the name of the ritual is associated with [[winter]].{{sfnm|1a1=Digital Daijisen|1y=1998a}}
== Name == ''Niiname-sai'' is the common name of the festival, but the same kanji can also be read ''Jinshō-sai''{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} or ''Niiname-no-Matsuri''.{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} ''Niiname'' can also be read ''Niinae'', ''Niinai'', ''Niwanai'', ''Niwanami'' or ''Nyūnami''.<ref name="万葉神事語辞典">{{Cite web|url=http://k-amc.kokugakuin.ac.jp/DM/detail.do?class_name=col_dsg&data_id=68770|title = 國學院大學 デジタルミュージアム}}</ref>
