[[Category:Shinto festivals]]

The '''Niiname-sai''' (新嘗祭, also read '''Shinjō-sai''' and '''Niiname-no-Matsuri''') is a Japanese harvest ritual.
The ritual is celebrated by the [[Emperor of Japan]], who thanks the [[Shinto]] deities for a prosperous year and prays for a fruitful new year. It takes place in the imperial palace and several large [[Shinto shrine]]s.
In pre-modern Japan, the date of the Niiname-sai was moveable, taking place on the last [[rabbit (zodiac)|Day of the Rabbit]] of the eleventh month of the old Japanese lunar calendar, but in the [[Meiji period]] the date was fixed at [[November 23]], and this date became a national holiday, [[Labor Thanksgiving Day]], in the [[Shōwa period]] after World War II.
== Ceremony == During the Niiname-sai, an ancient Shinto ritual that says thanks for the crops of the previous year{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} and prays for fruitfulness in the following year,{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} the [[Emperor of Japan]] says thanks to the {{illm|gods of heaven and earth|ja|天津神・国津神}}.{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} It is held in the [[Tokyo Imperial Palace|Imperial Palace]],{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} as well as [[Ise Shrine]]{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} and [[Izumo Shrine]].{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}}
== Date == Traditionally, it was held on the last [[rabbit (zodiac)|Day of the Rabbit]] in the eleventh month of the [[Japanese calendar|old lunar calendar]].{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}}
Since the [[Meiji era]] the date has been fixed on [[November 23]],{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} which corresponds to the modern public holiday [[Labor Thanksgiving Day]],{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} which was introduced in 1948.
As a ''[[kigo]]'', the name of the ritual is associated with [[winter]].{{sfnm|1a1=Digital Daijisen|1y=1998a}}
== Name == ''Niiname-sai'' is the common name of the festival, but the same kanji can also be read ''Jinshō-sai''{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} or ''Niiname-no-Matsuri''.{{sfnm|1a1=Britannica Kokusai Dai-Hyakkajiten|1y=2014}} ''Niiname'' can also be read ''Niinae'', ''Niinai'', ''Niwanai'', ''Niwanami'' or ''Nyūnami''.<ref name="万葉神事語辞典">[http://k-amc.kokugakuin.ac.jp/DM/detail.do?class_name=col_dsg&data_id=68770]</ref>
The first Niiname-sai following the [[Enthronement of the Japanese Emperor#The Daijo-sai|accession of a new emperor]] is called the ''Daijō-sai'' (大嘗祭, also read ''Ōname-Matsuri'' and ''Ōnie-no-Matsuri'').{{sfnm|1a1=Digital Daijisen|1y=1998}}<!-- Britannica also verifies this, but not the readings, and Britannica's separate article 大嘗祭 actually doesn't give the reading おおなめまつり. -->
== In literature == Book 19 of the ''[[Man'yōshū]]'' includes six poems (numbered 4273 to 4278) composed on the 25th day of the eleventh month of 752, the "''Niiname-kai'' poems".<ref name="万葉神事語辞典"/> The "''nyūnami''" is alluded to in one of the ''[[azuma-uta]]'' (songs of eastern Japan) included in Book 14.<ref name="万葉神事語辞典"/>
