{{Short description|Japanese harvest ritual}} {{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}} {{Infobox holiday | holiday_name = Niiname-no-Matsuri | type = | image = Niiname-sai.png | imagesize = | caption = | official_name = | nickname = | observedby = Japan | litcolor = | longtype = Religious | significance = [[harvest festival|harvest ritual]] | date = November 23 | scheduling = same day each year | celebrations = | observances = | relatedto = [[Labor Thanksgiving Day]], [[Daijosai]] }} The '''''Niiname-sai''''' (新嘗祭, also read '''Shinjō-sai''' and '''Niiname-no-Matsuri''') is a Japanese [[harvest festival|harvest ritual]].{{Japanese Imperial Rituals}}The ritual is celebrated by the [[Emperor of Japan]], who thanks the [[Shinto]] deities for a prosperous year and prays for a fruitful new year. It takes place near the [[Three Palace Sanctuaries]] in the [[Tokyo Imperial Palace]] and at several large [[Shinto shrine]]s. The first Niiname-sai for a new emperor is known as the [[Daijosai|Daijō-sai]] (大嘗祭), and is part of his [[Enthronement of the Japanese emperor|enthronement ceremonies]].
