{{Short description|Japanese harvest ritual}} {{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}} {{Infobox holiday | holiday_name = Niiname-no-Matsuri | type = | image = Niiname-sai.png | imagesize = | caption = | official_name = | nickname = | observedby = Japan | litcolor = | longtype = Religious | significance = [[:en:Harvest festival|harvest ritual]] | date = November 23 | scheduling = same day each year | celebrations = | observances = | relatedto = [[:en:Labor Thanksgiving Day|Labor Thanksgiving Day]], [[Daijosai]] }} The '''''Niiname-sai''''' (新嘗祭, also read '''Shinjō-sai''' and '''Niiname-no-Matsuri''') is a Japanese [[:en:Harvest festival|harvest ritual]].{{Japanese Imperial Rituals}}The ritual is celebrated by the [[:en:Emperor of Japan|Emperor of Japan]], who thanks the [[Shinto]] deities for a prosperous year and prays for a fruitful new year. It takes place near the [[Three Palace Sanctuaries]] in the [[Tokyo Imperial Palace]] and at several large [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]]s. The first Niiname-sai for a new emperor is known as the [[Daijosai|Daijō-sai]] (大嘗祭), and is part of his [[Enthronement of the Japanese emperor|enthronement ceremonies]].
In pre-modern Japan, the date of the Niiname-sai was moveable, taking place on the last [[:en:Rabbit (zodiac)|Day of the Rabbit]] of the eleventh month of the old Japanese lunar calendar, but in the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] the date was fixed at [[:en:November 23|November 23]], and this date became a national holiday, [[:en:Labor Thanksgiving Day|Labor Thanksgiving Day]], in the [[Shōwa period]] after World War II.
The Engishiki specified imperial involvement with four festivals, the [[Kinensai|Kinen-sai]], the two [[Ōharae-shiki]]s and Niiname-no-Matsuri for tribute.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book |last=Hardacre |first=Helen |title=Shinto: A History |date=2016-11-11 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-062171-1 |edition=Illustrated |location=New York |language=en}}</ref>{{rp|36}}
